{
  "$schema": "../../document.schema.json",
  "title": "Colors",
  "description": "In ACoreX, we have five primary colors — primary, secondary, success, warning, and danger — as well as seven accent colors, which are not defined by default but can be configured as needed.Each color has seven corresponding surface shades, which are used to define the colors of components and the overall application.Additionally, to ensure compatibility with TailwindCSS, the colors also include shades ranging from 50 to 950.",
  "sections": [
    {
      "title": "Main colors",
      "description": "By default, we use five colors, which you can modify or remove based on your application’s needs or design.For example, if you’re not using the secondary color, you can remove it from your theme. This way, all related code, variables, and secondary color styles will be eliminated from your project.This is demonstrated with an example on the <a href='/en-US/docs/styles/theming'>Theming</a> page.",
      "content": {
        "type": "table",
        "data": {
          "columns": ["Name", "Color"],
          "rows": [
            ["Primary", "<div class='color-card bg-primary-500'></div>"],
            ["Secondary", "<div class='color-card bg-secondary-500'></div>"],
            ["Success", "<div class='color-card bg-success-500'></div>"],
            ["Warning", "<div class='color-card bg-warning-500'></div>"],
            ["Danger", "<div class='color-card bg-danger-500'></div>"]
          ]
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "title": "On colors",
      "description": "In our color system, we use ON colors to ensure that each color has a suitable contrasting color to be placed on top of it. For example, on-primary is a color that provides sufficient contrast with the primary color.",
      "content": {
        "type": "table",
        "data": {
          "columns": ["Name", "Color"],
